column12: To begin, please select your district.
column13: Please select your school in Attleboro.
column14: Please select your school in Boston.
column15: Please select your school in Lowell.
column16: Please select your school in Revere.
column17: Please select your school in Somerville.
column18: Please select your school in Winchester.
column19: Given your preparation for teaching how  comfortable are you teaching at the grade-level you have been assigned?

column21: How confident are you in working with the  student body at your school?
column22: How many teachers in this school feel  responsible to help each other do their best?
column23: How many teachers in this school take  responsibility for improving the school?
column24: How many teachers in this school set high  standards for themselves?

column36: How often do teachers here collaborate to  make the school run effectively?

column51: At this school, how respectful are  students to each other?
column52: How adequate is your access to the  materials you need to effectively teach?
column53: How adequate is your access to the  technology you need to effectively teach?
column54: How adequate is the support you receive  for using technology?
column55: How sufficient is the physical space for  school activities?
column57: Overall, how effective is the support  students receive from non-teaching staff?
column58: How adeqaute is the number of non-teaching  support staff?
column59: How often are non-teaching support staff  available for students with non-academic issues?
column60: How often are non-teaching support staff  available for students who are struggling academically?
column61: Overall, how rigorous is the curriculum  that you are expected to teach?
column62: How coherent is the curriculum that you  are expected to teach?
column63: If one of your students transferred to  another district with a challenging assortment of courses, how well prepared  would he or she be?
column64: How well-rounded is the curriculum that  you and your colleagues teach?
column65: How able are you to integrate material  from different cultures into your class?
column66: How often do you integrate culturally  diverse content into your teaching?
column67: How often do you use teaching strategies  to facilitate learning among culturally diverse students?

column70: How involved have parents been in  fundraising efforts at your school?

column72: How often does the average parent help out  at your school?
column73: How effectively does this school connect  with immigrant families, providing translation when necessary?
column74: How effectively does this school respond  to the needs and values of the surrounding community?
column75: To what extent are all groups of parents  represented in the governance of the school?
column76: Overall, how effectively does this school  connect with the community?
column77: Relative to what you know of students this  age, how much effort did your students put forth in your class this year?
column78: If student work  from your classes was compared with work from  "average" Massachusetts classes of the same grades/subjects, how do  you think an objective observer would rate the work?
column79: If an observer sat in on one of your  classes for a week, how would she or he rate your students?
column80: How often do students at your school come  up with their own interpretations of material?
column81: How often do students apply ideas they  have learned to new situations?
column82: How often do students collaborate in class  to solve complex problems?

column84: In a typical week at your school, what is the average amount of time a student could spend in creative arts instruction or activities?
column85: In a typical week at your school, what is the maximum amount of time a student could spend in creative arts instruction or activities?
column86: In a typical week at your school, what is the minimum amount of time a student could spend engaged in physical activity?
column87: In a typical week at your school, what is the average amount of time a student could spend engaged in physical activity?
column88: In a typical week at your school, what is the maximum amount of time a student could spend engaged in physical activity?
column89: If there is anything you would like us to know about your school that we did not ask about, please tell us.
The school has current initiatives (PBIS, LAB, ILT) that have the potential to have a positive impact on culture and learning.  These initiatives need continued support.

Our school makes me proud. We have an old facility that is kept clean with a student friendly atmosphere. Our Adminstrators are genuinely interested in helping our school community thrive. We have a strong postitive culture that embraces diversity. Faculty challenges students to take academic risks.
Some of your questions require prior knowledge about someone else's actions. There should be a non-applicable or "Do not know" option.
This is a wonderful school full of hard working teachers and students. This administration is extremely supportive and helpful as well.
None
School is very old and not well maintained.  Seems to be short on cleaning staff and the school is very dirty.

The school culture at AHS is challenging if you're thin-skinned. Bullying among staff members is the worst kept secret and many people believe that department heads are puppets for central office and that friends get friends positions. That may be perception over reality, but it's a common belief.
Big staff, not aware of all activities in all subject areas.
We do amazing work with very little resources.  We need more staff, more technology, better facilities, etc. given our diverse population of students.
We desperately need a new physical building.  Nothing else matters nearly as much.  It really is everything.  It is about environment.
no

Our principal is extremely honest and open to discussion about anything. Even if I don't agree with a specific thing, he always makes sure I understand where he's coming from. I always feel appreciated, supported, and respected by him.

I find that Hyman Fine is by far the best elementary school in Attleboro. Our sense of community and the amount of collaboration and how much we care about each other is amazing. We don't get to always work across grade levels but I can honestly say all my coworkers care about me.
We have open classrooms, which presents challenges in terms of teaching and safety if an intruder ever entered the building.  We have no walls.

It was difficult to answer some of the questions regarding specials for example. Most classes have the prescribed amount, so more than 1 hour, but not quite 2, yet periodically specific students might be involved in extra activities. Student performance difficult to answer regarding sub groups.

I felt like many questions could be interpreted in more than one way. I felt there should have been an N/A choice. There is a positive atmosphere here that contributes to an amiable working environment. There is a sense of trust between administration and staff. Administration does not micro manage!
I am proud to teach here. It is a great school!

We have far too many initiatives going on. There is not enough time to TEACH. Some initiatives fail (flipped learning), but then we just go on to others. Some are great like MSTV, but there are way too many shoved down our throats - the latest being competency based learning.
I feel SO FORTUNATE to teach at Revere High.

Most teachers at Revere High School have reached a tipping point. Initiatives are added and previous initiatives are never revisited to lessen the burden. Communication is poor and enforcement of school policies is weak making it harder to try new pedagogy. Large class size also creates challenges.
You have 2 7s on the scale below
We've got an enormously hard-working faculty and students are remarkably well-integrated, with a unique mix of backgrounds, cultures and ability levels.
Class size effects the entire school experience for everyone involved.

We are a very understaffed school that does not always meet the needs of our students. Our class sizes are too high, and as a result, effective teaching may not always be possible especially with the increase in behaviors.
The school culture is strained and divided. The teachers are in desperate need of more common planning time where we can meet to discuss and plan curriculum.

The class size with inclusion (504s, IEPs, and ELLs) is relatively high and impacts learning.  Physically aggressive behaviors included in the general education classroom is also relatively high, impacts learning, and is quite concerning.

We have a new principal.  Our school has less staff per pupil ratio than any other elementary school.  Our school is consistently short staffed.  Our coaches are too busy doing other things to provide teacher/classroom support.
Many strong passionate, hard working staff.  Not enough support staff or counselors
This is an open spaced building that creates unusual needs and issues.

At times there seems to be disconnect between grades. Communication between staff members at times is weak at best. Team at time is just a word and not a full building culture. Too many individuals who seem as if they do not want to be part of a team.
I work with students who are below grade level in small group instruction, therefore,some questions were not applicable.
No

Our technology is getting better.  Training in technology would be helpful for some of us.  Many students struggle with academics, and would benefit greatly with some "hands on" classes which would put their academic learning into practice.

Seacoast is an excellent school, and it affords at risk students the opportunity to succeed; and in many cases, students do.  However, I do think that there are a number of areas where substantial improvement could be made, in particular: student discipline and use of financial resources.

I don't feel like the lack of response from parents and the community has been due to the school. The school has continually made an active effort to involve parents and the community--it's just that there has been little interest fropm the outside. We have tried different things, but to no avail.

All questions were answered as a Special Educator. My students' disabilities range from moderate to significant. Curriculum is specialized in the reading area and modifications are made for all. Services are provided in and out of the general education classroom.
This school does not have the proper behavioral management infrastructure to succeed. Teachers are the primary source of behavioral intervention.

Students who experience different influences inside and outside of school, including trauma, need a way to express themselves through creativity.There is a large gap between student ability, differentiation works to a degree, but some are being held back from their full potential.

Special education needs significantly out weigh special education services available. Needs of the population continue to grow but the resources available to support those growing needs do not. Additional counseling, speech, occupational therapy and special education support is much needed.

The Garfield Schoolis the best school in Revere because we have a principal that creates a warm supportive environment for staff and students.  I am proud to say I work there as great things are taking place each and every day. Test scores don t lie.

Curriculum is developmentally inappropriate.  Not enough time given for students to work at their ability. Teachers are micromanaged too much.  Way too much time on test prep and answering questions and looking at questions that will prepare students for tests.  Test data is not valid or reliable.
class sizes are too big, that is the only problem
Principal is intimidating and not helpful, assistant principal is even worse
poor school climate - leadership is lacking-
na
no
This survey was not geared toward non-teaching staff.
Special education needs and resources
This survey does not seem appropriate for me, a service provider.
Many of these questions were difficult to answer for related service providers.
We have many related service providers and special education classes.
Some of these questions and answers can be interpreted in many ways so the data needs to be analyzed appropriately.

We have a very diverse school from pre-school to fourth grade. We house and integrate many extreme special needs programs Our Paras are amazing in their interaction and instruction with students. We do not have enough paras or enough ELL staff. We are a hard working staff within our classrooms and w
Our past three years have been extremely difficult with administrative changes both in and out of the building that has impacted out school.
Teachers work extremely hard to meet the needs of all students.
Need more counselors and aides
We have an outstanding principal who works hard, and communicate well w teachers.  Teachers feel valued.  He takes discipline issues seriously.  Children have clear expectations regarding behavior.
My classroom is a sub-separate program, Insights, for students diagnosed with Autism. Students and teachers at Brennan are overall very receptive to the students in the Insights program.
student to staff ratio is too high; we have had too many budget cuts and lay offs; especially with support staff for special education

Standardized testing and comparing data has made teachers competitive with time, resources, and ideas. This competitiveness helps nobody, hurts school culture, and impacts students. Urban schools need more emotional councilors and social workers. Community building needs to be universally encouraged
The principal at BMS is approachable and understanding. He truly has the best interests of both students and staff at heart.

Our school has a very difficult time managing severe behaviors.Teachers seem to be quite entitled and have a difficult time working collaboratively with one another and trusting one another. Some teachers are willing to try new teaching strategies, while others are not.
We consistently are very short handed and lack adequate individual support for students struggling both academically and behaviorally. As a result, all students and overall learning goals suffer.
would like to see more opportunities to meet with colleagues from around the district for prof. dev. opps.
Answers are related to the special education population that comprises my class.
I'm very happy with the support teachers get from our administration.
This is my first year at Daley School.  I am very happy to be here and I look forward to improving my teaching practice in the years to come.
Class size is very high averaging 29 students. For core content teachers, ELA and Math, preparing students for standardized testing, this number is too high.

This is an extremely well-disciplined school where there is a climate of mutual respect. It is a very safe place where the needs of all students are constanlty being addressed, whether academic, behavioral, related to home or peer issues.
Questions on teacher and para compensation would have been interesting.

I think that almost everyone in our school works very hard to maintain a rigorous standard and teach all students. I think we could use improved support from coach teachers to help with materials and teaching struggling students. Also, students would benefit from more physical activity and arts.

The principal is a micromanager who appears to be more interested in his legacy than what the school needs and lacks real understanding of running a school and how to support and foster relationships with the staff. The staff is very unhappy, but this is being ignored because it isn't a "standard."

Yes, the fact that we spend many hours after school grading and preparing lessons as well as writing up recommendations and effective effort awards.  There are a great deal of other responsibilities that we attend to that are not teacher related or paid positions, that utilize our time.

Students lack opportunities to build community amongst each other e.g lack of traditions, rituals, assemblies. Everyday logistics need to be ironed out I.e system for getting supplies when they run outTeachers support each other and administrators  take time to talk with staff when approached
Great community/staff need more support
N/A
How comfortable are teachers observing each other and giving feedback to each other?Do you feel you gain anything from observing other colleagues?
Nothing
It is time to focus on lower performing teachers instead of the "good to great" philosophy.  The few make all the difference.
The school varies widely.  It was hard to answer some of the questions because many teachers are wonderful but many teachers do the bare minimum to get by with no repercussions.
I wouldn't want to teach anywhere else in Revere but here.
length of class period...  length of day...  hallway behavior

There is a lack of communication (from administrators to teachers) and a lack of consistency (in upholding and enforcing basic standards of behavior, school rules, expectations, etc.). Both of these issues have been ongoing and contribute to a disorderly and often frustrating school environment.
Class sizes are large and the school is bursting at the seams.   Teachers suppliment the provided curriculum with their own materials to fill in gaps in Pearson.
Average can be misleading because our population is highly varied, in socioeconomics, in culture, in parent involvement and communication, in choices to join activities at school, etc...

The students who are motivated or kind to one another are very different.  It is difficult to answer these questions as a class, because some students are very unkind and disrespectful and others are extremely motivated and kind.  Only a handful are unkind.
Student culture is in need of improvement
The class size at our school makes it difficult to work to the best of my ability.

We are a school with frequent administrative turn over.  In my 6 years teaching here, I've worked with 3 different principals and 4 different assistant principals (with a 5th coming in next year).  Administration seems to be a revolving door and it's a staff and school culture destroyer.

I think we are very lucky to work with the teachers that are at this school.  They have strong collegial relationships with each other, seek new strategies for teaching, and take initiative to improve the school.  With leadership changes, however, many feel unsupported in many ways and then burn out

The teachers do extraordinary work despite little guidance, support, or actual hands-on work from our administrators, particularly our principal. I wish we had strong leadership from someone who really wants to be a middle school principal, and is not just using this job as a stepping stone.
no
thank you

We are a school who has undergone some turnover with teachersover the past few years. There were less teacher transfers this year which should hopefully translate to more school pride and a better culture.

State issues rather than simply a district/school issues:  -student behavior and consequences (restrictions on suspensions promotes a culture of acceptance for seriously inappropriate behavior).-teacher safety (students with significant mental and emotional health problems)
My responses should probably have an asterisk as I started in February, taking over for a teacher who left mid-year for personal reasons.
N/A

This survey asked many questions that I could not answer. I do not feel I have the authority or knowledge to evaluate the school community as a whole, parents, or support staff. Also, many questions about rigor and how my students compare with others varies from class to class, student to student.
The classroom sizes are too large. I am teaching science classes where I am expected to leach labs with classes of over 30 students. Also, I am 1 of 4 science teachers in the whole school.
need behavioral support program

The new policy regarding students not being suspended for egregious behaviors puts students and teacher's safety at risk. It does not take into consideration that those students do Not consider anyone besides themselves and their own agendas. Minority is favored over the majority.
Some question were difficult to answer, especially the questions that involved knowing how physically active and how much time students spend on creative arts.
no
you asked about the principal, but being a High School, the House Deans and Department Heads are the people I interact with the most and I think they do a good to great job.
The principal does not value teacher experience.There is zero trust.
Some of the answers I felt did not fit the question as I saw it.

These questions were too vague, I mean really, "how often are students bullied?"Some are never bullied, some are always bullied.  Am I supposed to haven and answer "students are bullied 3 X week"???  How will this help anything?
We need common planning.
There is no loyalty from administrators towards teachers.  No attempt is made to help teachers find positive solutions.
This survey is way too long if you want us to carefully read and consider each response

Certain subject matter is not influenced by cultural diversity such as anatomy which is consistent through cultures except for certain diseases .  Be careful what you ask in regards to culture.  It is more about the mutual respect in the classroom and equal opportunity than curriculum.
There aren't any options for "not applicable."
I'm a special education teacher. Some of my answers may not be relevant to the general population. For those, I chose the middle option.

There is almost no time for teacher collaboration. Usually it is completed through multiple emails because people can't stay after school. On half days, where we should be getting professional development opportunities, our time is usually spent in pointless meetings.
n/a
No

The reading curriculum in our district is terrible. It is not diverse, it does not teach spelling, grammar, vocabulary. There is absolutely no structure to this program, they say the kids will eventually "get it", well they don't. They leave 8th grade not knowing how to spell, and knowing no grammar

Obsolete technology. Physical structure of the building is psychologically draining. Chips missing in stairs are a hazard. Students who fail still graduate. School offers "buy back" to somehow replace days missed in Honors level courses. Students very disrespectful to teachers.
Our Principal works hard each day to ensure that all students and staff feel that they are part of the Pyne Arts school community and engaged in instruction.
Add this question:  Are students passed when they have not met the curriculum standards?

What kind of support do teachers get from administrators?How often do administrators consult with teachers before making decisions that affect grading policy, classroom management, and teaching strategies?
Could there be a section that allows teachers to comment on (a) management strategies and (b) great activities that engage students?  Having specific "success" notes from teachers would be wonderful.

It feels as though Administration does not support or trust teachers as professionals. What they think and say goes. Everything is so micromanaged that it's defeating to try and do anything especially new or exciting things. Focus is so heavy on academics. View student/family as being right.
Our administration has high standards for teachers and students but are very human and supportive at the same time. I am eternally grateful to them.
The staff to student ratio is too high to be effective. Some teachers see 150 kids a day.

I love my school and am extremely proud and happy to come to work each day working with these amazing students, their families and such a friendly and supportive environment of colleagues and administrators! I love my job!

The climate of the school has declined greatly over the past few years. The behavior problems have increased greatly. Students are not effectively disciplined.  Violent student behavior is increasing daily. The school has become an unsafe teaching and learning environment.

Some questions were n/a. ...I also believe that the questions were leading. It is obvious what the survey is attempting to reveal. I do feel that it is somewhat underhanded because it is leading. However, I like to express my thoughts and I feel it's extremely important for teachers to have a say.
My department head works very hard and does a wonderful job. She is extremely dedicated and sets high expectations for her teachers. She is also thoughtful and kind.
for a large urban school, we are a close knit community of learners.
I teach severe special education. The Hill school has gone above and beyond to facilitate the learning and inclusive settings for my students throughout each day.

There were not many or any questions about support from your directors, it was all principal questions , yet we don't deal with the principals much as the assistant principal and directors, so most of the principal questions I answered were somewhat based on all 3 of them as a whole.

As a PE teacher I can't relate to being on grade level. Children grow at a different rate and the standards for PE go up to 5th grade. I teach K-4. I feel that most kids receive inadequate amount of exercise/play. Seeing a student once a week is not enough to develop and master physical skills.

Mistrust between staff and admin regarding the evaluation system.  Admin attempts to communicate goals/ideas but is not clear or concise about it, sometimes hard to follow. Staff wants more time for students to be creative and work on project based learning.
you dont mention the students who are most at risk and require the most for support- specificallythose resources and support and the process for getting students the programs they deserve and need
no

Our principal, Mr. Moccia, and assistant principal, Mrs. Martel are amazing leaders.  They hold high expectations for staff and for students. They treat staff and students with respect.  They give teachers the support they need to try new ideas in class.  They support a respectful school culture.

Some of the teachers in the building are unwilling to collaborate and are unkind and unfair to students.  We have good leadership in the building as far as our admin and coaches for ELA and Math.  Unfortunately, the culture of the building is highly negative due to specific staff.

Custodial staff has made a huge change to improve the physical plant but the night cleaning crew (not the same) is not effective in regular cleaning and maintenance of stairwells (stairs and walls), hallways, bathrooms both adult and student, classroom floors and the windows need to be cleaned.
I love teaching at Lowell high school and I consider myself to be veryLucky to get to work with our amazing and resilient students.

The principal is completely detached from the academic environment at this school.  He is rarely in the building.  He does not support a rigorous academic curriculum and told the teachers our only job is to make sure students enjoy coming to school.The building I am in is ready to fall apart.
How do we feel state-wide testing to impact classroom planning and curriculum?

Do we have a big enough budget to provide the students with the resources we need.Do teachers get paid for the extra time they put in after school. Are kids really respectful and follow instructions?  Do administrators follow through with correctconsequences? Why are admins. afraid of parents?

I teach 3 different homerooms throughout the day and as a whole, 2 of them are very hard working and the students are kind and supportive to their peers.  The 3rd homeroom, however, seemed to have a negative attitude that has been unfortunately contagious throughout the year.
The lack of administrative support when dealing with student discipline issues

Our school is incredibly diverse, thus many of the questions were difficult to answer.  As an example, rating how our students compare to "average" Massachusetts students was not fair.  A good portion (30-40%) of our students would be above average whereas many of our students would be far below

Teachers at our school feel that Upper Administration make too many top-down decisions, do not value teachers' opinions, and micro-manage areas that should belong to teachers. If one disagrees with UA, we risk harsh verbal attacks and criticism. This is not how to build a healthy, innovative school.

It seems that text books are becoming a thing of the past, and students are required to access and rely on the internet more and more. You did not ask how teachers feel about this in their particular content area. In math, I prefer not giving up text books, where all content is in one place.

we've had numerous initiatives, which a great when they start out and then are not sustained.Teachers need to be heard and respected by agreeing to takes risks and delegate responsibility to the staff and support staff. There needs to be consequences consistently for actions with a common mindset.
N/A

It is nearly impossibly to apply a survey such as this one to a huge school such as ours because there are very different sub-sets of students & student cultures to take accurately into account (the socio-economic, immigrant,  first-generation immigrant,)

Morale is low overall.  There has been high staff turnover in recent years.  Many staff feel overwhelmed and burnt out.  Many students do not take learning seriously; there is little to no accountability their academic performance.  We need more positive behavior support.
some teacher are rule and some teacher that I have, the way that they teach is really hard to understands.

I am the Physical Education teacher at our school, so my answers to some of the questions may vary from those of classroom teachers. Since my grade/age groups are for the entire school, and use of a different curriculum, some questions I find don't fit my classes as clearly.
none
There is no discipline routine from administration

Lowell High School's administration and structure are highly impacted by District and School Committee action and inaction. Systemic issues with municipal governance in Lowell, therefore, are reflected in outcomes at the High School.

The school needs more people who can help with social / emotional issues  1 social worker and 1 guidance counselor is not enoughThe principal and assistant principal can not focus on teacher feedback and professional development because they are always reacting to student "fires."

The school is very divided.  The good teachers are very good and engaged, and the bad are horrendous and appear to be here for the paycheck.  There are many who "bite off their nose to spite their face".

With our top down leadership model it's do what I say and no interest at all about my thoughts. We have one PTA parent, a para whose daughter attends the school.The curriculum is one size that fits all, with little/no differentiation for ELL and special ed.Teachers DO have the solutions. FRUSTRATING

Our principal destroyed all collaborative efforts between teachers and administration the very first day he took over.  He is rarely here and has no clue what is going on inside of classrooms.  He has been the most destructive force to this school that I have seen my entire teaching career.

There is not an equitable assignment of duties (lunch, recess, dismissal) between Special Education Teachers and General Education Teachers. Special Education teachers are seen as "support staff" not as educators.

Teachers need more freedom to be creative in teaching curriculum and making decisions collaboratively.  It is way too top down in this school when it comes to decision making regarding curriculum, grading, just about everything. Its shameful that teaching has become so micro-managed and ineffective.
We have a wonderful student/teacher collaborating culture.
More info. about the "health" of the buildings.  (sick building?)  More communication.

Communication about student issues (such as bullying situations) and school issues (scheduling) is not executed effectively.  Non-homeroom teachers (art, music, gym, OT, PT, etc.) are not treated the same as homeroom teachers in regards to planning time, duty assignment, technology resources.

column15: STEM Academy at the Rogers School

column89: There is a school culture that often seems to put academics after everything else. Expectations for student to master content are constantly lowered. State curriculum standards are not being met at some of the elementary/middle schools, so the high school standards are too far a reach for them.

The student body is incredibly diverse in all ways, including behaviorally, emotionally, motivationally, cognitively, and academically.  My class this year is extremely motivated and exceptionally talented, but my class last year was the opposite, so I rated in the middle.
Please take in to consideration the population of our school and the fact it is a City Wide School.

I like my school but we have had many personnel changes and my principal and assistant principal are leaving and it's upsetting and influences the way I am answering questions this year--I might have answered some things differently if there wasn't so much uncertainty in the future.
My school is a great place to work.  The building is filled with teachers who really care about the children.  Most of the administration is 100% invested as well.  It is a community.

Very disturbed that Science and Social Studies are such a low priority.  Literacy Modules spend too much time focusing on a few standards, and I do worry that our students are not getting a balanced education, and are missing a common background knowledge.

I think the administration at our school is great. I think about half the teaching staff is excellent and the other half is mediocre. I think our biggest weakness in terms of teaching is special education staff/support.
I love working at this school,been here 23 years.
Lacking a strong administration.  Administration is afraid of parents and afraid to discipline students.

The major issue is the lack of respect that the students show to the faculty. My students can be belligerent, and have little/no consequences. There is also one grade level that thinks that they are superior to everyone else, and likes to talk negatively about the school and other faculty members.
A discipline system. I would like to know more about how we can implement a better/different discipline system that works.
The Murkland School has great leaders, that's why we are successful!!

The way curriculums are in pre-packed kits and set up, leave almost no interaction between the disciplines. There is very little interdisciplinary work done.School building and grounds are very poorly kept. This is speaks volumes of the students attitudes toward building and school materials.
